\begin_layout Title
Innovations in Dairy Value Chains - Evidence from Uganda
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We need a better title
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Policy changes, the injection of foreign direct investment in processing
 plants aimed at export, changing diets of an increasingly demanding urban
 and rural population and technological progress have substantially altered
 the entire dairy value chain in Uganda.
 Using a combination of primary and secondary data on different actors throughou
t the value chain, we document both exogenous and endogenous technological
 and institutional innovations to adapt to and take advantage of the rapidly
 changing environment.
 We exploit the fact that the sector seems to be evolving at two speeds,
 with one area highly focused on production for export processors and another
 area mainly catering for the local market.
 We find that integration in modern value chains is associated with increased
 technology adoption among farmers, formalization of supply agreements,
 and professionalization of inter-mediation.
 Milk collection centers that bulk and chill the milk are important not
 only for quality assurance; they also complement the weak service sector
 by provide a range of services to its suppliers.
 Fierce price competition and substantial uncertainty means processes are
 still searching for the optimal level of vertical integration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dairy value chain has undergone substantial changes in the last few
 years.
 These changes are driven by a variety of factors, both affecting the demand
 and supply of milk.
 First, local consumption of milk is increasing.
 Poverty has decreased dramatically over the past two decades.
 Higher incomes resulted in rapidly increasing consumption of dairy products,
 products that generally are assumed to be highly income elastic.
 Especially in cities, consumers become aware of the health benefits of
 dairy products and are persuaded by an ever increasing supply, both in
 informal milk shops and emerging supermarkets.
 Second, Uganda's strong liberalization record also means processing plants
 were constructed.
 Often, this was in the form of green field investment to exploit the low
 production price of milk in parts of the country that makes the sector
 very competitive in the international market.
 On the supply side, technological innovation, supported by institutional
 changes, have also resulted in increased production, better quality, and
 smoother functioning supply chains and markets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this study, we highlight some of the key drivers the led to the transformatio
n of this value chain.
 We do this by comparing data between two different areas that have evolved
 quite differently over time.
 In the so-called southwestern milk shed, located around the town of Mbarara,
 the value chain has changed dramatically in the course of only a few years,
 with processors converting milk into complex products with a long shelf
 life, such as UHT and casein, mostly for export.
 At the same time, in a nearby area with comparable production levels, the
 so-called central milk shed, most of the production and trade is still
 largely informal, and the milk that is processed is generally sold as pasteuriz
ed milk in Kampala.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The data used was collected at different nodes in the value chain.
 Upstream, we interviewed cattle farmers that produce milk, most of it for
 the market.
 These farmers generally sell raw milk at the farm gate to traders, the
 second category of actors we collected data from.
 Traders, in turn, sell this unprocessed milk to milk collection centers,
 the third category of actors we interviewed.
 A significant number of farmers also sell directly to milk collection centers,
 often because they are members of the cooperative that runs the center.
 There is also an important informal market, with farmers selling directly
 to neighbours, especially in the central milk shed.
 Another important actor in the chain is the processor, who sources milk
 from milk collection centers, and in the southwestern milk shed also directly
 from traders.
 We collected primary data on 1,600 producers, 700 small traders, and 100
 milk collection centers.
 We also collected qualitative data at two processors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find that integration into a modern dairy value chain goes hand in hand
 with the adoption of higher yielding animals.
 In the southwestern milk shed, more than 82 percent of the herd consists
 of crossbred cows.
 We see that the central milk shed is catching up with the southwestern
 milk shed in terms of adoption of crossbred cows.
 While 10 years ago, only 8 percent of the herd consisted of improved animals,
 this has now become almost 50 percent.
 We find that especially farmers that are located close to milk collection
 centers, guaranteeing a stable market for their milk supply, are replacing
 local Ankole cows with cross-breeds.
 We also find that producers that have better access to acaricides, the
 medicine
