\end_inset

 used to spay against ticks, are more likely to adopt cross-breeds, as these
 animals are particularly susceptible to East Coast Fever.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also find that often agreements exist between producer and buyer (generally
 a trader or milk collection center).
 However, mostly these are non-binding oral agreements.
 Indeed, as producers interact with buyers on an almost daily basis and
 payments are usually done weekly, more formal agreements may not add much
 to an already close relationship.
 While the average farmer sells to more than one neighbour, he or she tends
 to work with a single trader.
 At the same time, we do find that technology adoption is higher among farmers
 that report more formal agreements with their clients.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dairy value chains is also characterized by the existence of many small
 traders and transporters who collect milk using bicycles or motorbikes
 in villages and take it to milk collection centers or processors.
 There seems to be a reasonable degree of competition among these middlemen.
 Our data suggests that traders and transporters tend to be more professional
 in the southwestern milk shed: they visit significantly more clients on
 the average day and transport quantities that are three times as large
 as traders and transporters in the central milk shed.
 Over time, traders have also embraced technology to facilitate their work.
 For instance we see that almost all traders use mobile phones and many
 use motorbikes.
 We generally do not find differences between the two milk sheds.
 We do find that virtually all traders in the southwestern milk shed use
 stainless steel milk storage containers for transport, while this is often
 done using jerrycans in the central milk shed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Arguable the most fascinating link in the chain are the milk collection
 centers.
 Located at strategic places in rural areas, these centers collect and chill
 the milk in large coolers, often powered by generators.
 However, our data suggests that these centers are much more than just collectio
n points: they also offer a range of services to their clients, ranging
 from credit to veterinary services, particularly if they are cooperatives.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we also provide some insights on processing companies.
 The largest processors are located in the southwestern milk shed, and process
 milk mostly for export.
 Their main challenges are procuring enough milk, especially in the dry
 season.
 Their operations are also greatly constrained by the poor industrial base
 in Uganda: most of the packaging material needs to be imported from Kenya.
 Processors are very heterogeneous in terms of vertical integration: while
 some only engage in processing, others also own milk collection centers
 and/or milk trucks, while others even have their own milking cows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rest of this article is organized as follows.
 We start by describing the evolution of demand.
 We then briefly touch on the policy context in which the dairy value chain
 has developed.
 Next, we describe how the milk sold by the average farmer flows through
 the value chain, separately for the southwestern and the central milk shed.
 We then zoom in on producers and look at adoption of crossbred cows, milk
 production and market participation.
 We also devote some attention to contracting between farmers and buyers.
 Next, data on traders and transporters is presented, and a comparison of
 their profiles between the central and southwestern milk shed is made.
 We then turn to milk collection centers, where ownership is an important
 qualifier and briefly mention some stylized facts about how processors
 experiment with different degrees of vertical integration.
 A final section concludes.
\end_layout

