\begin_layout Section*
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper describes the dynamic dairy sector in Uganda.
 Comparing an area that is generally oriented towards dairy processing for
 export to an area that is more oriented towards the local market, we identify
 key differences in technologies used and institutional organization among
 the different value chain actors.
 We do so using primary data collected among 1,600 producers of various
 scale, 900 traders and 100 milk collection centers.
 We supplement our analysis of primary data with secondary data from the
 DDA and with qualitative data obtained from two processors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We describe a reasonably modern dairy value chain in the southwestern milk
 shed, with farmers supplying substantial amounts of milk to traders that
 specialize in collecting milk at the farm gate and transporting it to milk
 collection centers or directly to the processor.
 There is almost universal adoption of crossbreeds and producers have daily
 transactions with one and the same buyer.
 In the area that is more oriented toward the local market, the adoption
 of crossbreed cows is increasing, but still only one in two cows is improved.
 More is sold to neigbours, and producers seem less loyal to traders and
 milk collection centers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Seasonality is an important constraining factor in the dairy sector in Uganda.
 This seasonality may also help explain the paradox that despite the fact
 that processors produce below capacity, prices collapse during the rainy
 season.
 The seasonality is expensive for milk collection centers, because they
 can only run at full capacity for a few weeks per year.
 This may result in under investment in capacity in areas where milk production
 is highest.
 During the rainy seasons, tanks fill up quickly, depressing prices.
 The same arguments likely hold for traders.
 During the rainy season, there is probably a shortage of traders and farmers
 compete for space in the milk tanks of the traders.
 Seasonality is exacerbated by climate change and a lack of a feeding industry.
 Zero grazing where cows are fed using silage and hay using the dry season
 and access to water from dams is likely to increase production also during
 the dry season, attracting more capacity to the area.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is also surprising that in the southwestern milk shed, despite the fact
 that there are many more milk collection centers, competition between them
 seems to be lower.
 Producers stick to one milk collection center, and prices offered are substanti
ally lower than prices offered by alternative marketing channels, especially
 during the rainy season.
 It seems that producers prefer a guaranteed destination for their milk
 important, and are prepared to receive a lower price in return.
 At a more aggregate level, milk collection centers in the southwest keep
 selling to processors even at very low prices.
 Also here, the centers may be prepared to pay a price for a good relationship
 with the processor.
 Or, it may also be that switching buyer is not straightforward in the short
 run and does not pay for the short period of the rainy season.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Processors also warn that the large informal sector is a threat to the industry.
 Often, people prefer the raw milk because they thing processed milk is
 diluted.
 Milk collection centers that are cooperatively owned appear to be an effective
 way to guarantee quality.
 At the same time, the fact that the DDA is also much more active in the
 southwestern milk shed may indicate that a repressive approach is needed
 for some actors in the value chain.
 
